Hi there.<br />Collision response can be a very complicated problem so keep that in mind.<br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />I'm writing some collision code<br /></div></blockquote><br />Basically you want to adjust your algorithm so it looks like:<br />1. move objects<br />2. check for intersections<br />3. separate intersecting objects<br />4. adjust velocities of colliding objects<br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />if so move the player to his previous x position<br /></div></blockquote><br />You can't do that if you want decent-looking collisions.<br />You have to find the &quot;shortest separation vector&quot; between the two colliding rectangles.<br />Then you separate the objects and adjust their velocities.<br />This is called &quot;non-continuous&quot; collision (bump uses &quot;continuous&quot; collision which is more complicated)<br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div><br />I'd like to be able to slide along the box while holding two keys<br /></div></blockquote><br />There are 2 variables that will affect collisions: friction and restitution.<br />These two variables affect how the velocities are adjusted AFTER the collision.<br />Here is the tutorial I wrote a while ago:<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://2dengine.com/doc/gs_collision.html">http://2dengine.com/doc/gs_collision.html</a><!-- m --><br />HTML5 demo:<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://2dengine.com/doc/tutorials/html5/index.html">http://2dengine.com/doc/tutorials/html5/index.html</a><!-- m --><br />Note that if the restitution (bounce) is always 0 and friction is always 0<br />then the equations can be simplified even further.<br /><br />Things get quite complicated if want to have torque/rotation,<br />realistic transfer of momentum (depending on mass)<br />or a lot of moving objects (broadphase) so it's important to keep it as simple as possible<br />when writing your own collision system.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://love2d.org/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=69">ivan</a> — Fri Apr 01, 2016 8:00 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
